    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-21T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-21T10:00:00-05:00" n="186"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d186">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–2154: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_RWS1"
                            >Robertson</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName>
                        Meeting, Geneva, May 21, 9:45 a.m.:</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d186fn1">A memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_JUA1"
                            >Johnson</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>, not
                        printed, dated May 21, indicated that <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                            >Pyun</persName>’s appointment with <persName corresp="#p_SWB1"
                            >Smith</persName> was set for approximately 9:45 a.m.
                        (795.00/5–2154).</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-21T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 21, 1954—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>92. Repeated information Department <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 276,
                    Tokyo 78. For <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAH1">Dean</persName>. Tokyo pass <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1"
                        >CINCUNC</gloss>. Department pass Defense.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Before meeting of 16 this morning <persName corresp="#p_SWB1"
                            >Smith</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName>
                        discussed and agreed on handling of meeting and <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                            >Pyun</persName>’s presentation his 14 points. <persName
                            corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_RWS1"
                            >Robertson</persName> strongly urged <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                            >Pyun</persName> amend his second point along lines our paragraph 2,
                        telegram 90 to Seoul, <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 266, Tokyo
                            77.<note n="2" xml:id="d186fn2">Dated May 20, <ref target="#pg_298">p.
                                298</ref>.</note>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> agreed ask instructions delete
                        language after “also” and insert “in accordance with the constitutional
                        processes of the <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>”.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>His request to <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> presumably
                        encoded in <gloss target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss>’s 91 to Seoul.<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d186fn3">Not printed.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Several speakers in meeting of 16<note n="4" xml:id="d186fn4">See <ref
                                target="#d187">
                                <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                            </ref>.</note> for same reasons also urged same suggestion re second
                        point and urged <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> get approval
                        from <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> and revise point before he
                        makes speech Saturday.<note n="5" xml:id="d186fn5">May 22.</note> Except for
                        points 12 and 13, US and other 14 find second point only real difficulty in
                            <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName>’s proposal. If <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> approves <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                            >Pyun</persName>’s suggested change above, Allies will be able give
                        general support all <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName>’s points but
                        12 and 13 on which they still have reservations and need time consult home
                        governments.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Accordingly urgent have favorable <persName corresp="#p_RS1"
                            >Rhee</persName> reply before <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                            >Pyun</persName> makes speech so he can change second point. <gloss
                            target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss> would appreciate speedy processing
                        telegram 91 to Seoul and any reply to <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                            >Pyun</persName> if that could come back by State channels <gloss
                            target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss> if <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                        Government so desired and mentions this matter to you. Suggest might be
                        useful in your discretion you deliver encoded text in our 91 personally to
                        Acting Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_CCH1">Cho</persName> with
                        whatever use of above points you feel advisable recognizing delicacy
                        referring to private communication <pb facs="0330" n="304" xml:id="pg_304"/>
                        between <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> and possibility <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> may not have full text 14 points.
                        However in view importance this matter <gloss target="#t_USDel1"
                            >USDel</gloss> hopes deadline noon Saturday Geneva time can be met if
                            <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s response favorable.<note
                            n="6" xml:id="d186fn6">
                            <p>The following message was sent <gloss target="#t_niact1"
                                    >niact</gloss> to Geneva for <persName corresp="#p_SWB1"
                                    >Smith</persName> from <persName corresp="#p_DAH1"
                                    >Dean</persName> in telegram 16 from Tokyo, also sent to the
                                Department of State as telegram 2882, May 22: <quote
                                    rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“Your 92 to Seoul reached us Tokyo. Pursuant suggestion your
                                        90 did not show or discuss <persName corresp="#p_PYT1"
                                            >Pyun</persName>’s 14 points with <persName
                                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>. Since <persName
                                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> has always insisted on
                                        plebiscite believe might be better rely on <persName
                                            corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName>’s direct request, but
                                        would make abundantly clear you are not accepting 12 and 13.
                                        If <persName corresp="#p_PYT1">Pyun</persName>’s statement
                                        put forward and Communists don’t just reject, gives you
                                        basis further modification.</p>
                                    <p>“<persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> returning
                                        Seoul Sunday. <persName corresp="#p_DAH1">Dean</persName>
                                        leaves late Sunday afternoon for Washington.” (396.1
                                        GE/5–2254)</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
